WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.353
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.230 --> 00:00:08.840
DAWN ENGLE: My name
is Dawn Gifford Engle.

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:11.750
And my husband
and I 23 years ago

00:00:11.750 --> 00:00:14.510
decided to start
something called PeaceJam.

00:00:14.510 --> 00:00:20.820
And it's our program which
allows young people to connect

00:00:20.820 --> 00:00:23.040
with Nobel Peace Prize
winners, and to learn

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.660
how to become
leaders themselves,

00:00:24.660 --> 00:00:26.280
and to change the world.

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:30.420
And we have been
going for 21 years.

00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:33.960
We have 1.3 million
young people who've

00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:35.850
participated in our program.

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:38.290
And we're all over the world.

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:42.630
So it sounds like
a big thing, right?

00:00:42.630 --> 00:00:44.730
That's our mission.

00:00:44.730 --> 00:00:47.850
But when we started, it was
just a couple of factory worker

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:49.200
kids from Detroit.

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:51.150
Ivan and I are just a
couple of factory worker

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:52.230
kids from Detroit.

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:53.970
And he had a big idea.

00:00:53.970 --> 00:00:58.920
And his big idea came out
of a summer of violence

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:02.160
in Denver, Colorado, a
lot of gang violence.

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:07.600
And he is a passionate
Bulgarian, wild man, artist,

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:11.010
the former lead singer of a punk
rock band called The Ramrods--

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:12.500
who are still
infamous in Detroit,

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:15.000
so you can only imagine how
over the top they were--

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.340
and writer for "CREEM" magazine.

00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:19.710
And he's very artistic.

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:23.670
And he as an artist was living
in the worst part of Denver

00:01:23.670 --> 00:01:26.440
and a place where there
was a lot of gang violence

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:26.940
that summer.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:29.460
The newspapers called it
the "summer of violence."

00:01:29.460 --> 00:01:32.670
And 13-year-olds were killing
14-year-olds, drive-by

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:34.570
shootings-- it was bad.

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:37.820
And one day he saw somebody
in his neighborhood--

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:41.010
young kid, 14 years
old-- carrying a gun.

00:01:41.010 --> 00:01:44.040
And he called the kid and
his friends over and he said,

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:45.070
what's going on?

00:01:45.070 --> 00:01:47.070
You're not in school anymore.

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:48.930
I see you during the day.

00:01:48.930 --> 00:01:49.690
What's going on?

00:01:49.690 --> 00:01:51.690
And they said, well,
we have a business

00:01:51.690 --> 00:01:53.119
and we have a turf to protect.

00:01:53.119 --> 00:01:54.660
And he goes, OK,
you have a business,

00:01:54.660 --> 00:01:56.937
maybe it's selling drugs.

00:01:56.937 --> 00:01:58.770
If you have a business,
you have to be smart

00:01:58.770 --> 00:02:00.240
and you need to be in school.

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:03.614
And they said, no, we're out
of school, we don't care.

00:02:03.614 --> 00:02:06.280
He was really worried about them
so he kept talking and he said,

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:07.988
who's the President
of the United States?

00:02:07.988 --> 00:02:09.479
And they said, I
don't know, and I

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:11.970
don't care because he
doesn't represent us.

00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:13.350
They were really disengaged.

00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:14.760
But he kept talking to them.

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:16.860
He was so worried, he
kept talking, and talking,

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:19.320
and they stumbled over
the topic of South Africa,

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:22.080
because the miracle in South
Africa had just happened,

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:24.450
this peaceful transfer
of power in South Africa

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:25.320
had just happened.

00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:27.750
And these young
people, they knew all

00:02:27.750 --> 00:02:31.140
about Desmond Tutu,
Nelson Mandela.

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:32.280
They went off.

00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:34.740
They went on and on about
how inspiring they were,

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:37.590
and they stood up to
the man, and they did it

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:40.030
without violence, and they
got their country back.

00:02:40.030 --> 00:02:45.660
And Ivan just had this big
light bulb go off over his head

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:46.660
and he said, wow--

00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:49.170
if we can put young people
together with Nobel Peace Prize

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:52.110
winners, maybe
that energy that's

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:53.490
going in a negative
direction, it

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:54.810
can go in a positive direction.

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:57.630
Maybe their lives
can be transformed.

00:02:57.630 --> 00:02:59.760
Nobel Peace Prize winners
who are walking the talk,

00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:03.060
putting their lives on the line
for peace around the world,

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:05.950
these should be the role models
that these young people have.

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:09.270
And so he came and he
started talking to me.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:12.600
And he started talking
to me because I'm

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:13.920
like the opposite of Ivan.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:16.410
I'm very linear.

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:17.820
I'm an economist.

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:19.712
I worked for Congress
for 13 years.

00:03:19.712 --> 00:03:21.420
I was the youngest
woman ever to be chief

00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:23.130
of staff for a US senator.

00:03:23.130 --> 00:03:25.267
And when I was in
Washington, D.C.,

00:03:25.267 --> 00:03:26.850
I was one of the
very first volunteers

00:03:26.850 --> 00:03:29.310
for the International
Campaign for Tibet.

00:03:29.310 --> 00:03:31.290
So I knew the Dalai Lama.

00:03:31.290 --> 00:03:34.450
So he came and said, we have
to meet with the Dalai Lama,

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:35.950
we have to meet
with the Dalai Lama,

00:03:35.950 --> 00:03:37.540
get us a meeting
with the Dalai Lama.

00:03:37.540 --> 00:03:39.457
And he kept talking,
and talking, and talking

00:03:39.457 --> 00:03:40.290
about this big idea.

00:03:40.290 --> 00:03:43.230
And finally I said,
OK, I will do it.

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:45.270
We got the meeting
with the Dalai Lama.

00:03:45.270 --> 00:03:47.040
And Ivan said, great,
when is the Dalai

00:03:47.040 --> 00:03:48.150
Lama coming to Denver?

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:50.310
And I said, no, no, no, no.

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:53.380
No, we have to go to India.

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:57.390
And he said, I have $1.72
in my checking account--

00:03:57.390 --> 00:03:58.380
which was true.

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:01.470
So we had to borrow
money from friends.

00:04:01.470 --> 00:04:04.950
And we went and flew to India.

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:06.319
The Dalai Lama loved the idea.

00:04:06.319 --> 00:04:07.860
And he said, don't
just work with me,

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:09.776
though, work with these
other Nobel laureates.

00:04:09.776 --> 00:04:11.670
He gave us a list
of seven others.

00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:15.270
And we went back to
Ivan's artist's loft

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:19.740
in Denver with no heat, asbestos
hanging out of the ceiling,

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:21.540
we've got our coats
on, it's cold.

00:04:21.540 --> 00:04:24.570
But we have a big
idea, and a telephone,

00:04:24.570 --> 00:04:26.340
and the Dalai Lama said yes.

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:29.970
So we just colcalled the rest of
the Nobel Peace Prize winners,

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:31.140
honest and truly.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:35.780
Hey, Desmond Tutu, this is Dawn
from Denver, you don't know me

00:04:35.780 --> 00:04:38.700
but we have a big idea and
the Dalai Lama said yes.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:41.910
And we were able to get eight
Nobel Peace Prize winners

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:45.570
to say yes to be our board.

00:04:45.570 --> 00:04:47.430
Before we were
incorporated, before we

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:49.980
had any money, before
we had a curriculum,

00:04:49.980 --> 00:04:51.540
before we had
anything we were just

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:54.750
two people who were so
on fire with this idea

00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:57.030
that we got eight Nobel
Peace Prize winners

00:04:57.030 --> 00:05:00.120
to agree to be our board.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:03.060
And we asked them 10 years
later at our 10th anniversary,

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:06.600
why did you say yes to us?

00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:08.310
And they said, well,
it was a good idea

00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:09.742
but it was a really hard idea.

00:05:09.742 --> 00:05:11.700
No one had ever brought
all the Nobel laureates

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:13.080
together like that before.

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:14.830
And I figured if
anybody could do it,

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:16.800
it was those two
crazy Americans who

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:18.570
had been sitting on
my front porch step

00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:21.690
for a week waiting
for a meeting with me.

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:24.120
And it's an example that
we give to young people

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:28.950
because passion matters, ideas
matter, being tenacious really

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:29.820
matters.

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:33.390
And as you see here,
we ended up actually

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:36.110
being married by Desmond Tutu.

00:05:36.110 --> 00:05:37.870
We were friends,
we were colleagues,

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:40.140
we started doing PeaceJam,
and we fell in love,

00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:42.450
and Desmond Tutu
married us in his church

00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:44.281
in Cape Town, South Africa.

00:05:44.281 --> 00:05:46.530
And then at the end of the
service, he pulled us aside

00:05:46.530 --> 00:05:49.290
and he said, now, people who I
marry, they never get divorced.

00:05:49.290 --> 00:05:51.930
So it was like, yes, sir.

00:05:51.930 --> 00:05:54.424
So we are stuck with each
other for all of eternity,

00:05:54.424 --> 00:05:55.840
but we're really
happy about that.

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:58.100
We're very, very
happily married.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:00.600
And and we're a great team.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:03.420
And we've now ourselves
been nominated 17 times

00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:06.330
for the Nobel Peace Prize,
so pretty incredible.

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:09.390
And this is what we've
been able to do so far.

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:12.750
It's almost up to 1.3
million young people

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:14.970
who have participated in
our yearlong programming.

00:06:14.970 --> 00:06:17.700
What happens is young people
study the life of a Nobel Peace

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:20.130
Prize winner, they
look at what's

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:23.010
going on in their own community,
they create a project that

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:24.780
makes things better
in their own community

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:26.940
or in some other
part of the world,

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:29.022
they get to spend a weekend
working side-by-side

00:06:29.022 --> 00:06:31.230
with this Nobel Peace Prize
winner whose life they've

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:34.320
studied and presented
them their project.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:35.820
Then they go out
and do the project,

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:37.830
they gather again
six months later,

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:39.760
and the cycle goes
on year after year.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:43.590
So it's education, which is our
curriculum; inspiration, which

00:06:43.590 --> 00:06:45.020
is the Nobel Peace
Prize winners;

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:47.130
an action, the most
important part.

00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:49.050
It's easy to come
up with a good idea,

00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:50.880
it's hard to
implement a good idea.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:53.460
So we teach those skills so
that young people can become

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:55.560
empowered agents of change.

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:57.990
And we have-- oh,
the slide needs

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:02.130
to be updated-- we're up
to 33 million projects

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:05.430
and we're up to 145
countries for our One Billion

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:07.453
Acts of Peace Campaign.

00:07:07.453 --> 00:07:07.953
Thanks.

00:07:07.953 --> 00:07:11.310
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:11.810 --> 00:07:15.860
So we were doing a
speech in Silicon Valley.

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:17.600
We were at Microsoft
headquarters

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:18.860
and we were doing a speech.

00:07:18.860 --> 00:07:22.010
And we got offstage and somebody
from Google came up to us.

00:07:22.010 --> 00:07:23.030
And it was Meng--

00:07:23.030 --> 00:07:23.990
Chade-Meng Tan.

00:07:23.990 --> 00:07:28.020
Has anybody heard of Meng, who
started Search Inside Yourself

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:30.410
and meditation here at Google?

00:07:30.410 --> 00:07:36.680
And he bowed to us and he said,
you're doing what I want to do.

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:38.720
I want to create world peace.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.210
And I'm going to kidnap you
and take you to someplace

00:07:41.210 --> 00:07:43.700
where they have better food.

00:07:43.700 --> 00:07:44.550
And so he did.

00:07:44.550 --> 00:07:48.920
He kidnapped us, put us in
his car, drove us to Google.

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:52.400
And we sat there for
three, four hours--

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:53.870
we just kept
talking and talking.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:55.640
We were so excited
about what could happen

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:57.930
if we started working together.

00:07:57.930 --> 00:07:59.675
And so we were able to get--

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:05.720
Google is our lead donor and
tech developer for the Billion

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:06.710
Acts of Peace Campaign.

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:07.440
It's incredible.

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:13.310
We've had over 100 Googlers
working on-- and YouTubers

00:08:13.310 --> 00:08:14.300
working on--

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:15.200
this project.

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:18.650
We have half a million dollars
in Google AdWords' budget

00:08:18.650 --> 00:08:19.250
every year.

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:23.450
And it's been an
extraordinary partnership.

00:08:23.450 --> 00:08:27.230
And we are almost
tripling every year.

00:08:27.230 --> 00:08:29.330
We're definitely going
to make the billion goal.

00:08:29.330 --> 00:08:31.380
We were just at
Mountain View doing

00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:33.049
our annual strategic
planning meeting,

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:35.640
and the campaign is going great.

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:38.450
The campaign itself, the One
Billion Acts of Peace campaign,

00:08:38.450 --> 00:08:42.107
has been nominated nine times
for the Nobel Peace Prize.

00:08:42.107 --> 00:08:44.190
And we are up for the Nobel
Peace Prize this year.

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:48.170
So cross your fingers, maybe
on October 6 we will win

00:08:48.170 --> 00:08:49.880
and even more people
around the world

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:51.560
will be able to join the effort.

00:08:51.560 --> 00:08:56.120
But the idea is that, you know
what, our governments are just

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:58.520
polarized, or they're
paralyzed, or they're not

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:00.710
dealing with the really
crucial issues that

00:09:00.710 --> 00:09:04.880
are facing humanity, so it's
time for us to act ourselves.

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:06.560
We're not going to
wait any longer.

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:09.770
We're going to get together--
businesses, nonprofits,

00:09:09.770 --> 00:09:15.840
universities, cities, towns,
high schools, young people,

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:18.800
old people, everybody,
just a citizens' movement

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:22.310
where we work on what the
Nobel laureates have identified

00:09:22.310 --> 00:09:24.620
as the 10 key issues
facing humanity--

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:26.960
things like alleviating
extreme poverty,

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:30.710
access to clean water for
everybody, ending racism

00:09:30.710 --> 00:09:33.620
and hate, rights
for women and girls.

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:37.100
So we have a campaign with a
lot of high-integrity moral

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:37.850
leadership.

00:09:37.850 --> 00:09:39.890
And this is what we're
focused on doing.

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:42.050
Implementing our
transformational education

00:09:42.050 --> 00:09:42.550
program.

00:09:42.550 --> 00:09:44.799
We just got a big grant from
the European Commission--

00:09:44.799 --> 00:09:46.220
the European Union--

00:09:46.220 --> 00:09:48.590
to work with young
people who have just

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:52.280
arrived in Europe who
are refugees-- mainly

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:54.830
Muslim refugees-- and
helping to integrate them,

00:09:54.830 --> 00:10:01.280
social inclusion grant working
to build stronger communities

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:04.242
where there is a lot of
divide right now in Europe.

00:10:04.242 --> 00:10:05.450
So we're expanding in Europe.

00:10:05.450 --> 00:10:08.149
We just started in Singapore,
we just started in Colombia,

00:10:08.149 --> 00:10:09.440
we're about to start in Turkey.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:11.310
So we're expanding
around the world.

00:10:11.310 --> 00:10:14.750
And we have our One Billion
Acts of Peace Campaign.

00:10:14.750 --> 00:10:16.700
I believe we're going
to reach that goal.

00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:20.330
And then I believe that the
Nobel Peace Prize winners--

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:22.070
they're my bosses.

00:10:22.070 --> 00:10:24.110
When Ivan and I
started this program--

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:25.850
we're not on the board.

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:29.900
We could be fired tomorrow
without any reason.

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:33.140
It's Colorado, so you can fire
anybody without any reason.

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:34.880
And we are just employees.

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:37.647
We really wanted this program
to be of, by, and for the Nobel

00:10:37.647 --> 00:10:38.480
Peace Prize winners.

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:40.880
We wanted it to be their
educational outreach program

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:42.170
to the youth of the world.

00:10:42.170 --> 00:10:44.270
And I'm certain that
once we hit a billion

00:10:44.270 --> 00:10:47.870
they'll say, great,
now let's go for 10.

00:10:47.870 --> 00:10:50.460
And then we have a film series,
the Noble Legacy Film Series,

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:51.670
which is really incredible.

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:53.499
It captures the spirit,
and the essence,

00:10:53.499 --> 00:10:55.790
and the cutting-edge work of
all of our Nobel laureates

00:10:55.790 --> 00:11:01.010
around the world, people like
the Dalai Lama or Desmond Tutu,

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:01.940
who are getting older.

00:11:01.940 --> 00:11:03.920
And we want to capture
them, and their essence,

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:06.200
and their spirit for
all time to share

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:08.090
with people around the
world as a continuing

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:09.512
source of inspiration.

00:11:09.512 --> 00:11:11.970
And we've been nominated a lot
of times for the Nobel Peace

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:12.620
Prize.

00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:18.050
I was saying to Jeremy it's
a little nerve-wracking right

00:11:18.050 --> 00:11:19.850
now, because we're
getting phone calls

00:11:19.850 --> 00:11:22.605
at our house from the
Norwegian Nobel Committee.

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:27.680
So I think we're
on the short list--

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:29.930
at least they keep calling.

00:11:29.930 --> 00:11:31.550
So we'll see what happens.

00:11:31.550 --> 00:11:36.830
But yeah, it's wonderful for
Nobel Peace Prize winners

00:11:36.830 --> 00:11:38.570
to believe so strongly
in this movement

00:11:38.570 --> 00:11:43.100
and it's wonderful to see
that it's being recognized

00:11:43.100 --> 00:11:46.160
internationally as well.

00:11:46.160 --> 00:11:49.490
And here's a shot from
our Desmond Tutu film,

00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:52.150
beautiful film called
"Children of the Light,"

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:54.920
and the rest of the
films in this series.

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:57.070
So that's all I
really wanted to share

00:11:57.070 --> 00:11:59.995
with you is that this
work is going forward.

00:11:59.995 --> 00:12:01.870
I don't know if you saw
at the United Nations

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:04.300
yesterday-- a lot of things
happened at the United Nations

00:12:04.300 --> 00:12:07.010
yesterday, some good, some bad.

00:12:07.010 --> 00:12:11.564
But Governor Brown of
California was there

00:12:11.564 --> 00:12:13.480
and he was talking about
something good, which

00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:16.150
is that even though our
president has decided

00:12:16.150 --> 00:12:20.530
to not implement the
Paris Climate Accords,

00:12:20.530 --> 00:12:23.407
cities, and states,
and businesses,

00:12:23.407 --> 00:12:25.240
and all sorts of people
are getting together

00:12:25.240 --> 00:12:27.860
and we're going to
implement it ourselves.

00:12:27.860 --> 00:12:31.400
And so these are the kinds
of citizen, action citizen

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:33.880
mobilization--

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:36.287
working together, we can
actually create the change

00:12:36.287 --> 00:12:37.120
that we want to see.

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:39.190
And we're going to go
ahead and start doing it.

00:12:39.190 --> 00:12:39.880
We are doing it.

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:43.360
We have 33 billion projects
so far and we're on our way

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:44.650
to a billion.

00:12:44.650 --> 00:12:47.740
And hopefully someday our
leaders will follow us.

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:49.570
So that's all I wanted
to say to give you

00:12:49.570 --> 00:12:50.990
an overview of PeaceJam.

00:12:50.990 --> 00:12:51.490
Thanks.

